"Xie S.-P., Du Y., Huang G., Zheng X.-T., Tokinaga H., Hu K., Liu Q.","Decadal shift in El Niño influences on Indo-western Pacific and East Asian climate in the 1970s",2010,"Journal of Climate","23","12",,"3352","3368",,,10.1175/2010JCLI3429.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77954464103&partnerID=40&md5=31f992b07fda05f9176821f1a954129b","International Pacific Research Center, Department of Meteorology, University of Hawaii at Manoa, Honolulu, Hawaii, United States; LED, South China Sea Institute of Oceanology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Guangzhou, China; LASG, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing, China; Ocean University of China, Qingdao, China","Xie, S.-P., International Pacific Research Center, Department of Meteorology, University of Hawaii at Manoa, Honolulu, Hawaii, United States; Du, Y., LED, South China Sea Institute of Oceanology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Guangzhou, China; Huang, G., LASG, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing, China; Zheng, X.-T., Ocean University of China, Qingdao, China; Tokinaga, H., International Pacific Research Center, Department of Meteorology, University of Hawaii at Manoa, Honolulu, Hawaii, United States; Hu, K., LASG, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing, China; Liu, Q., Ocean University of China, Qingdao, China","El Niño's influence on the subtropical northwest (NW) Pacific climate increased after the climate regime shift of the 1970s. This is manifested in well-organized atmospheric anomalies of suppressed convection and a surface anticyclone during the summer (June-August) of the El Niño decay year [JJA(1)], a season when equatorial Pacific sea surface temperature (SST) anomalies have dissipated. In situ observations and ocean- atmospheric reanalyses are used to investigate mechanisms for the interdecadal change. During JJA(1), the influence of the El Niño-Southern Oscillation (ENSO) on the NW Pacific is indirect, being mediated by SST conditions over the tropical Indian Ocean (TIO). The results here show that interdecadal change in this influence is due to changes in the TIO response to ENSO. During the postregime shift epoch, the El Niño teleconnection excites downwelling Rossby waves in the south TIO by anticyclonic wind curls. These Rossby waves propagate slowly westward, causing persistent SST warming over the thermocline ridge in the southwest TIO. The ocean warming induces an antisymmetric wind pattern across the equator, and the anomalous northeasterlies cause the north Indian Ocean to warm through JJA(1) by reducing the southwesterly monsoon winds. The TIO warming excites a warm Kelvin wave in tropospheric temperature, resulting in robust atmospheric anomalies over the NW Pacific that include the surface anticyclone. During the preregime shift epoch, ENSO is significantly weaker in variance and decays earlier than during the recent epoch. Compared to the epoch after the mid-1970s, SST and wind anomalies over the TIO are similar during the developing and mature phases of ENSO but are very weak during the decay phase. Specifically, the southern TIO Rossby waves are weaker, so are the antisymmetric wind pattern and the North Indian Ocean warming during JJA(1). Without the anchor in the TIO warming, atmospheric anomalies over the NW Pacific fail to develop during JJA(1) prior to the mid-1970s. The relationship of the interdecadal change to global warming and implications for the East Asian summer monsoon are discussed. © 2010 American Meteorological Society.",,"Anti-symmetric; Atmospheric anomaly; Climate regime shift; Down-welling; East Asian summer monsoon; Equatorial Pacific; In-situ observations; Indian ocean; Interdecadal changes; Kelvin waves; Monsoon winds; Ocean warming; Rossby wave; Sea surface temperature anomalies; Southern Oscillation; Teleconnections; TiO; Tropical indian ocean; Tropospheric temperature; Western Pacific; Wind anomalies; Wind patterns; Atmospheric pressure; Atmospheric temperature; Atmospheric thermodynamics; Global warming; Ocean currents; Nickel compounds; atmosphere-ocean coupling; atmosphere-ocean system; decadal variation; downwelling; El Nino-Southern Oscillation; global warming; Kelvin wave; Rossby wave; sea surface temperature; teleconnection; wave propagation; Far East; Indian Ocean; Indian Ocean (North); Indian Ocean (Tropical); Pacific Ocean; Pacific Ocean (Equatorial); Pacific Ocean (Northwest)",,,,,,"Alexander, M.A., Blade, I., Newman, M., Lanzante, J.R., Lau, N.-C., Scott, J.D., The atmospheric bridge: The influence of ENSO teleconnections on air-sea interaction over the global oceans (2002) J. Climate, 15, pp. 2205-2231; Alory, G., Wijffels, S., Meyers, G., Observed temperature trends in the Indian Ocean over 1960-1999 and associated mechanisms (2007) Geophys. Res. Lett., 34, pp. L02606. , doi:10.1029/2006GL028044; An, S.-I., A review of interdecadal changes in the non-linearity of the El Nino-Southern Oscillation (2009) Theor. Appl. Climatol., 97, pp. 29-40; An, S.-I., Wang, B., Interdecadal changes in the structure of ENSO mode and their relation to changes of ENSO frequency (2000) J. Climate, 13, pp. 2044-2055; Annamalai, H., Xie, S.-P., McCreary, J.-P., Murtugudde, R., Impact of Indian Ocean sea surface temperature on developing El Niño (2005) J. Climate, 18, pp. 302-319; Arai, M., Kimoto, M., Simulated interannual variation in summertime atmospheric circulation associated with the East Asian monsoon (2008) Climate Dyn., 31, pp. 435-447; Ashok, K., Behera, S.K., Rao, S.A., Weng, H., Yamagata, T., El Niño Modoki and its possible teleconnection (2007) J. Geophys. Res., 112, pp. C11007. , doi:10.1029/2006JC003798; Carton, J.A., Giese, B.S., A reanalysis of ocean climate using Simple Ocean Data Assimilation (SODA) (2008) Mon. Wea. Rev., 136, pp. 2999-3017; Chang, C.P., Zhang, Y., Li, T., Interannual and inter-decadal variations of the East Asian summer monsoon and tropical Pa